.us/j/87477024015?pwd=gVpnKPDuNsoZ0giaFoA7gicVcI6afV.1","participants":["colin.costigan@marketersindemand.com,nina.belina@marketersindemand.com,josh@ptoexchange.com,nathalie.mintjens@marketersindemand.com","nina.belina@marketersindemand.com","josh@ptoexchange.com","nathalie.mintjens@marketersindemand.com"],"transcript_url":"https://app.fireflies.ai/view/01KFKMRPY76TQZWM9FT1QBFYBA","organizer_email":"colin.costigan@marketersindemand.com"}'::jsonb,
    '{"label":"neutral","confidence":0.83,"bullets":["Flagged need for improved HubSpot data integrity, with 500+ unused contact fields and 200 workflows.","Mapped next steps for audit cleanup including attribution tracking, lead management, and UX clarity.","Requested structured documentation outlining UX site map, persona strategy, and rationale for changes.","Raised concern about duplicated testimonials and AI images; content audit assigned to Carmen.","Agreed marketing dashboard enhancements depend on foundational HubSpot fixes and SLA alignment."],"highlights":[{"quote":"There’s over 500 properties in HubSpot just for contacts... 95% of them rarely if ever used.","speaker":"Colin Costigan"},{"quote":"We need to define what is an MQL, when do we hand it off, and what has to happen.","speaker":"Carmen Williams"},{"quote":"I don’t want photos of fake people on my website... I want to be real.","speaker":"Rob Whalen"}],"topics":["attribution","lead-management","delivery","hubspot","ux","data"],"model":"openai/gpt-4-2024-06","version":1,"generated_at":"2026-01-29T23:25:00Z"}'::jsonb,
    '{"fireflies_summary":{"notes":"## **HubSpot Audit and Data Integrity**\n\nThe HubSpot system requires a thorough cleanup and standardization to improve data quality, lead source tracking, and reporting accuracy.\n\n- **The audit revealed over 500 contact properties with 95% rarely used, plus 200 overlapping active workflows causing confusion and inefficiency** (28:10)  \n    - This complexity leads to inconsistent data, reducing confidence in marketing and sales reports.  \n    - Colin explained that seven different lead source fields create confusion and unclear attribution.  \n    - The team plans to clean up unused properties, unify lead source definitions, and streamline workflows.  \n    - This cleanup is critical to accurately measure campaign effectiveness and optimize resource allocation.\n\n- **Lead source properties for deals must remain unchanged due to their importance in sales compensation and reporting** (33:20)  \n    - Josh emphasized that deal-level source fields like \"Inbound\" or \"Demanding Event\" are required and heavily used.  \n    - Contact-level lead sources are separate and need clearer definitions and better management.  \n    - Carmen noted the need for alignment and suggested an additional meeting between marketing and sales to finalize source tracking structure.\n\n- **Data quality issues include 237,000 contacts with many duplicates and non-business emails like Gmail and iCloud** (40:50)  \n    - Nina and Natalie acknowledged that duplicate merging is manual and time-consuming but feasible.  \n    - The team agreed on prioritizing cleanup of contacts without emails and possibly restricting demo requests to business emails only.  \n    - Natalie noted some companies accept personal emails to maintain long-term nurture despite job changes, requiring nuanced rules.  \n    - Rob pushed for removing irrelevant contacts, like venture capitalists, and questioned the value of personal email contacts.\n\n- **The HubSpot cleanup and lead management improvements are part of three main initiatives: database integrity, attribution reporting, and lead management process** (47:53)  \n    - Colin offered to map out property definitions, responsibilities, and workflows as part of their retainer.  \n    - Carmen and Josh plan to discuss specifics next week with Rob to align on priorities and resource allocation.  \n    - The team recognized the need for clear sales enablement instructions and communication to prevent past issues with property usage.  \n    - Sam, the current HubSpot administrator, is involved as a contractor to assist transition and provide historical context.\n\n## **Lead Management and Marketing-Sales Alignment**\n\nEstablishing clear lead qualification criteria and handoff processes is essential to improve pipeline visibility and conversion tracking.\n\n- **Current lead qualification lacks clarity on MQL vs. SQL definitions and lead disqualification tracking** (35:54)  \n    - Stephanie highlighted the importance of defining these terms clearly and tracking reasons for lost deals or unqualified leads.  \n    - Carmen observed that marketing and sales roles overlap, causing inconsistent lead management.  \n    - Colin emphasized cleaning up lifecycle and lead status stages to unify communication between teams.  \n    - The goal is to enable clear handoffs and ensure leads are properly nurtured or disqualified with documented reasons.\n\n- **A structured lead management process including SLAs, qualification criteria, and next steps will align marketing and sales teams** (50:39)  \n    - Rob suggested using company email verification as a gate for demo requests to improve lead quality.  \n    - Carmen agreed and explained that demo requests are high-commitment leads likely to be SQLs, bypassing MQL stages.  \n    - The team agreed to develop a tight lead management framework covering budget, authority, timeline, and other qualification factors.  \n    - This will reduce wasted effort on unqualified leads and optimize sales follow-up.\n\n- **Sales enablement materials and clear communication of new processes are needed for successful adoption** (29:42)  \n    - Josh asked if New North provides sales enablement, and Colin confirmed it is standard practice.  \n    - Past gaps in communication about HubSpot changes led to unused properties.  \n    - The team will formalize documentation and training to prevent future misalignment.\n\n## **Marketing Campaigns and Reporting Improvements**\n\nCampaign design and reporting need refinement to improve attribution, lead capture, and conversion tracking.\n\n- **Current reporting dashboards provide high-level views but lack detailed campaign attribution and source cleanup** (05:37)  \n    - Colin showed reports tracking contacts created, MQLs, SQLs, meetings, and closed deals by source.  \n    - Carmen noted the audit identified lead management and attribution tracking as key areas needing improvement.  \n    - The team plans to standardize source fields and break out channels more granularly, separating paid, organic, and other traffic sources.\n\n- **New campaign designs include lead magnets focused on PTO assessment and healthcare employee retention, aimed at LinkedIn lead gen** (07:54)  \n    - Colin explained LinkedIn lead gen forms reduce friction by keeping users on the platform with pre-filled info.  \n    - Campaign assets include landing pages and infographics based on existing research and whitepapers.  \n    - Upon approval, email and LinkedIn nurture sequences will roll out to promote these campaigns.\n\n- **Website feedback highlighted the need for clearer UX strategy, brand consistency, and content audit** (16:34)  \n    - Carmen requested a sitemap and rationale for page structures, personas, and navigation to understand the user journey.  \n    - Nina offered to compile existing brand and persona discussions into one document for clarity.  \n    - Rob flagged issues with duplicate testimonials and stock or AI-generated images; immediate removal of fake testimonials was prioritized.  \n    - Carmen will lead a content audit to validate testimonials and enforce no AI image usage as a brand guideline.\n\n## **Website UX and Content Strategy**\n\nThe website needs ongoing development with clearer UX direction and authentic content to support marketing goals.\n\n- **Current website builds lack a unified UX strategy and persona research, causing uncertainty about navigation and content flow** (17:31)  \n    - Carmen expressed that previous work felt like disconnected page creation without clear user journey mapping.  \n    - The team agreed to push live agreed-upon pages like homepage and industry pages, then iterate based on user feedback.  \n    - A living, evolving website approach was endorsed to allow continuous improvement.\n\n- **Content authenticity and brand trust are critical; fake or duplicated testimonials and AI images must be removed** (20:17)  \n    - Rob emphasized real images and names for testimonials to avoid competitor comparisons showing fake content.  \n    - Josh highlighted privacy concerns and lack of image permissions as reasons for absent real photos.  \n    - The immediate fix involves removing problematic images and possibly hiding images until permission is secured.  \n    - Carmen will conduct a content audit to ensure all website content aligns with brand authenticity standards.\n\n- **Future website updates will incorporate industry-specific research and statistics to demonstrate domain expertise** (25:58)  \n    - Josh shared plans to include turnover data and challenges in healthcare and other industries on relevant pages.  \n    - This approach aims to increase visitor trust and engagement by showing understanding of sector-specific pain points.  \n    - The website will serve as a dynamic resource reflecting ongoing research and marketing priorities.\n\n## **Team Coordination and Next Steps**\n\nThe team is aligning on communication, meeting cadence, and responsibilities to drive execution on audit findings and marketing initiatives.\n\n- **Weekly or biweekly meetings will be established between Carmen, Natalie, Nina, and others to dive deeper into strategy and initiatives** (55:30)  \n    - Josh and Rob will be involved as needed to provide sales and leadership input.  \n    - These sessions will focus on campaign execution, reporting improvements, and lead management processes.\n\n- **New North will draft a detailed plan outlining cleanup steps, responsibilities, and timelines as part of their current retainer** (37:44)  \n    - This plan will include database cleanup, attribution tracking, and lead management process improvements.  \n    - Carmen will review and coordinate with Josh and Rob to finalize priorities and resource needs.\n\n- **Sam will support the transition as a contractor, providing historical knowledge and helping answer process questions** (53:24)  \n    - The team agreed his involvement is essential to efficiently resolve technical and data issues.  \n    - Coordination between Sam and New North will ensure continuity and knowledge transfer.\n\n- **Immediate technical fixes include removing duplicate testimonials and fake images from the homepage to improve brand trust** (24:58)  \n    - New North will prioritize these updates while broader content audits and UX strategy develop.  \n    - Carmen will gather examples of preferred image styles to guide future content decisions.","outline":null,"keywords":["HubSpot Audit","Lead Management","Campaign Attribution","Website UX","Database Cleanup","Marketing Qualified Lead (MQL)"],"overview":"- **HubSpot Audit:** Over 500 contact properties audited; 95% unused. Cleanup needed for better data quality and lead source tracking.  \n- **Lead Source Management:** Deal-level source fields essential for sales. Contact-level fields require clear definitions to prevent confusion.  \n- **Data Quality Issues:** 237,000 contacts contain duplicates and non-business emails. Prioritize cleaning up and removing irrelevant contacts.  \n- **Lead Management Process:** Need for clear SLAs and qualifications to align marketing and sales, reducing wasted efforts on unqualified leads.  \n- **Website Improvements:** Focus on genuine content; remove duplicates and AI images. Regular updates needed to showcase industry-specific insights.  \n- **Team Coordination:** Establish weekly meetings to dive into strategy and assign clear responsibilities for ongoing cleanup and marketing initiatives.","action_items":"\n**Carmen Williams**\nCoordinate with Josh and Rob for additional weekly strategic deep-dive meetings post wider team calls (39:11)\nLead content audit focusing on testimonials, image authenticity, and brand guidelines including prohibiting AI-generated images (21:01)\nReview and clarify UX strategy, sitemap, and persona insights by receiving compiled documentation from Nina (18:30)\nCollaborate with New North to outline how to address database, attribution, and lead management cleanup initiatives and who is responsible for each (43:42)\nConduct ABM strategy development focused on Healthcare Enterprise segment with Natalie, Nina, Josh, and Rob (55:22)\nPrepare for upcoming detailed lead management discussions to define MQL/SQL criteria and lead qualification workflows (50:41)\n\n**Josh Reinhard**\nDiscuss CTA strategies and website feedback with Carmen and team to refine approach and policy (13:09)\nSupport database cleanup by providing insights into deal properties and participation in discussions on data rules and merging duplicates (40:50)\nCollaborate with Carmen and New North team to kick off lead management process refinement and data integrity initiatives (43:42)\nCoordinate to involve Sam (former HubSpot admin) in knowledge transfer to aid cleanup and optimization efforts (46:33)\n\n**Nina Belina**\nShare documentation and presentations related to campaign background, research, and lead magnet strategy with Carmen and team (08:38)\nCompile all brand, persona, and copy discussions into one comprehensive document for Carmen’s review to aid alignment on UX and navigation (19:19)\nCollaborate with Natalie and Colin on database audit cleanup plan and proposal of actionable next steps for PTO Exchange (56:17)\n\n**Nathalie Mintjens**\nAssist in sharing campaign and audit presentations and related documentation (08:38)\nHelp lead the database assessment and manage developer resources to explore automation or improved workflows for cleanup (42:32)\n\n**Colin Costigan**\nProvide full presentation and report links to Carmen and wider team including the HubSpot audit and campaign tracking overviews (05:24)\nPrioritize removing duplicate testimonial and replacing/removing AI-generated or stock images on homepage (24:58)\nSupport setup of standardized data definitions, property mapping, and cleanup workflows within HubSpot in collaboration with New North team (35:54)\nPrepare a summary of next steps and processes as part of existing retainer, clarifying scope and timeline (38:09)\n\n**Rob Whalen**\nFlag and encourage quick removal of duplicate testimonials and images lacking authenticity on website (20:41)\nProvide user perspective and feedback on CTA, navigation, and marketing content authenticity (14:28)\nAssist in evaluating quality of contact database and prioritizing clean filters (44:32)\n"},"migrated_from":"contract_meetings","original_id":"e4b18ccc-a008-48e7-a54f-fb2e806c435f","master_marketer":{"status":"migrated"}}'::jsonb,
